Observed a coast night snake (Hypsigiena ochrorhynchus) consuming a side-blotched lizard (Uta stansburiana) on the Grotto trail within the Santa Monica Mountains National Recreation Area on April 13. I first noticed the side-blotched lizard at 3:45 pm with its head in a burrow on the side of the trail, but when I tried to pick it up it became apparent something was holding on to its head. I stayed and watched as the night snake slowly emerged form the burrow to consume its prey over the course of 45 minutes. Once finished the night snake slithered off the trail into some low shrub cover. It was no more than 12 inches long.

My trail highlight of the day. I found this small Western Diamondback during this morning's hike right on the trail.

I have to say, for as many snakes as I have come across I have never been so close to stumbling right over one but, something made me look down just as the trail was about to make a turn. Glad I did.

 He was maybe less than two feet in length and was sitting next to a kill he had apparently just made when I approached. His meal: a Merriam's Kangaroo rat. He stayed next to the rat for a while before sizing it up to start to consume it. I have seen plenty of rattlesnakes but never one who had just made a kill and was about to eat. I watched for a while and took a little video. But I didn't stay for the entire show. On my way back to the trail head I checked to see if he might be digesting off trail near where I spotted him. But he was no where to be found. About 3 hours had passed anyway, so I knew that I wouldn't likely see him again anyway.

This is the second striped racer I've come across this summer eating a lizard.  The first was eating an alligator lizard (looked like it had been run over by a mountain bike mid-meal), this one is actively eating a still-alive western fence(?) lizard.

I was walking down a dirt road and hear a squeel.  As I get closer to the place where I heard the noise, I see a ball of snake and rat tumble out of the shin oaks.  Finding that I don't have my camera, I rush inside to get it.  When I return, the rat is dead but still in the snakes coils.  I get off one shot before the snake gets scared and "runs" off.  I tried to back away to encourage it to finish its meal but it doesn't look back.  Since I don't think it is coming back, I go take pictures of the rat (next observation).  After taking the pictures, I left it there in hopes that the bullsnake would return.  Unfortunately, I don't think it ever did.
This one was dug up a toad.

This is one of my favorite observations.  I drove up on this snake that had a toad in its mouth.  When I got out to take pictures, it pushed the toad across the road.  When it got to the edge, it threw its body up the side of a sand ledge and pulled the toad up.  It was quite incredible to watch.

The Slangverklikkers alerted me to the presence of this cobra (otherwise I would never have seen it). It had its head stuck down a hole for ages, and I thought it may have run out of solar power because it was cold and drizzling at the time (the weather not the cobra).

About 45 mins after first seeing it, it pulled up its head with a massive frog in its jaws. I have never seen such a big frog here! Could the frog have bloated with the effects of the venom? Or perhaps it just looks enormous because it is being squashed to fit in the cobra's mouth...? Do we get bullfrogs in the karoo?

The pics are rubbish coz I took them through a window and did not want to go any closer for fear that the snake would regurgitate its meal, which is just a waste. The day was so cold, that I thought the snake would be more likely to regurgitate when it was already thermodynamically compromised.

It took about 20 mins for the frog to go down. And after some rather icky looking gagging, the cobra gently wandered off to look for further munchies.

With crab out of the way and in deep water the frog kept the pressure on and swam strongly, so that the snake could not coil around it. The snake soon gave up trying and went long and rigid until its tail touched the bank. It hooked this around a sedge and reeled in the frog, dragging it onto land, whereupon it threw its coils around the frog and all went still, apart from an occasional twitch from the frog, or tightening of the snakes coils, and Sirius and Jupiter appearing in the gloaming. After dark we retired to set up camp, and about an hour later on return the snake had just finished swallowing the frog. On next inspection 10 minutes later there was no trace of anyone.

A Karoo Prinia chattering somewhere in a bush next to the path ahead of me, drew my attention when I noticed vigorous shaking of vegetation close to the ground, which I took to be the related to the Prinia at first. Only when I took a closer look with my binoculars, did I spot the distressed Agama, rigid and slowly opening and closing its mouth - and then it became clear that the cause of the apparent distress was the grip of the snake across the chest area just behind the front legs.
The snake then deliberately maneuvered its mouth sideways towards the head of the Agama, and after about four minutes after first spotting it, it had aligned the Agama's head to be pointing straight into its mouth for the swallowing process to begin.
The snake then suddenly moved forward about eight inches, and seemed to use the rock to stabilise the Agama to get the head into its mouth, then it swung around again locating the its prey alongside its body for some more maneuvering, before moving out of sight into the vegetation behind the rock. Dennis did get a glimpse of the snake again, with just the tip of the tail of the Agama still visible, about 10 to 15 minutes after first observation.
Lesson to be learnt - listen to the birds - they often advertise the presence of predators.

FOCAL POINT: The racer (one of two posts for this encounter, the other being for the anole).

DESCRIPTION/CONTEXT: Walking to a gas station in Daytona Beach, I caught sight of the juvenile racer at the edge of the sidewalk, somewhat hidden by surface debris. I immediately reached down and snagged the little serpent -- only then realizing it was locked in combat with the Brown anole. If I'd known they were in combat, I wouldn't have caught them. Now in hand, however, I was surprised to see that neither organism was willing to give up the fight, especially the racer. They kept at it with each other in my hand, the racer eventually overcoming the anole. As the racer actually began to consume the anole, I put them down. It was an unexpected encounter to say the least, and now I feel compelled to check twice before snagging any juvenile racers!

I prefer my observations to be inline with current taxonomic standards as deployed by iNaturalist (as opposed to my personal beliefs) so that this and other observations are readily accessible to iNaturalist users with greater efficiency and usability. I was very lucky to document one of the rarest moment.

Here's the story behind this documentation, i got a call of 2 snakes fighting for around an hour just outside an entrance of a society. description: This obs for the snake predating on the frog.

I came across the pair apparently shortly after the snake had bitten the toad, around 14:30. In the video the adder can be seen giving the toad a second bite.
The snake started swallowing the toad at 14:38, the toad still struggling strongly. The toad stopped moving at around 14:41.
Initially I started filming on my phone as the snake was blocking the path to my camera and I didn't want to disturb it. An hour in (15:30), it was apparent that the snake was untroubled by the various humans and cats watching it, and I swapped to the camera.
By 16:50 the snake had swallowed the toad up to its hips. At 17:16 it partially regurgitated the prey and started swallowing again.
At 17:36 it again regurgitated a large portion of the toad - its front legs and feet were visible.
At 17:56 only the back legs were still protruding.
The toad was completely swallowed at 18:09, 3.5 hours in all.
The video (3mins 30 sec) is edited and speeded up 2x.

DISTRIBUTION: Eastern half of USA (Burbrink, 2001); Extreme eastern USA (Anonymous, 2022; HU, 2022)

OTHER NAMES: Elaphe obsoleta alleghaniensis (Garmann, 1884); Elaphe obsoleta deckerti Brady, 1932; Elaphe alleghaniensis quadrivittata (Conant and Collins, 1991); Pantherophis alleghaniensis quadrivittata (Conant and Collins, 1991).
SPECIMEN: 1 adult
DATE: 6 April 2022
LOCALITY: Old State Road 905, Key Largo, Florida 33037 USA
LATITUDE, LONGITUDE: 25.0921, -80.4423
DISTINCTIONS: Adult Tropical Yellow Ratsnakes are distinguished by 2 longitudinal dark brown or black stripes on both sides (lateral) against a lighter background of bright golden-yellow.  Ventral (underside) is pale yellow.
DISTRIBUTION: Extreme south Florida and the Keys (Burbrink, 2001).
HABITAT: Spends a lot of time underground but is also arboreal climbing trees for prey.
OBSERVATION: A loud screaming was heard 11.8 m (25 ft) to the right and 13.7 m (45 ft) high in the trees.  The origin of the continuous scream was a large, dense nest.  Then something large fell from the nest making a loud thump hitting the ground.  With the aid of binoculars, the screaming squirrel could be seen running around the nest.  At the base of the tree was a large Tropical Yellow Ratsnake constricting a young Fox Squirrel.
DISCUSSION: Apparently, the falling behavior is common in these snakes.  Rat Snake predation in Fox Squirrel nests is unusual because adults usually attack and drive them off.
SIMILAR PREY SPECIES: Fox Squirrels can have black on their heads and white noses.  The Eastern Gray Squirrel, Sciurus carolinensis Gmelin, 1788, does not.
IMPORTANCES: (1) Rare nest predation of Tropical Yellow Ratsnake on a Big Cypress Fox Squirrel, resurrection of a subspecies, and a common name for the subspecies.

I came across this unusual scene while hiking back to my car this afternoon.  What I think is happening here is that the racer probably tried to predate the alligator lizard, only to have the alligator lizard clamp down on the snake's head.  When I came upon them, the snake wasn't moving much.  I sat and watched for a bit, but then noticed a mountain biker coming down the trail.  When I stood up so he could see me, I must have startled the lizard, because all of a sudden the snake got free, and zipped off into the tall grass on the side of the trail.  After a second or two, the alligator lizard also dashed off, albeit in the other direction.  I felt a little badly about disturbing the situation, but really there was a good chance one or both animals would have been run over by the biker, who was demonstrating his species' usual level of spatial awareness.  (ie none whatsoever.  I'm still not sure he ever saw me.) All in all, it was quite a surprising encounter.

description: Hamilton Pool Preserve is a historic swimming hole which was designated a preserve by the Travis County Commissioner's Court in 1990. Located 3/4 mile upstream from its confluence with the Pedernales River, Hamilton Creek spills out over limestone outcroppings to create a 50 foot waterfall as it plunges into the head of a steep box canyon. The waterfall never completely dries up, but in dry times it does slow to a trickle. However, the pool's water level stays pretty constant, even during periods of drought. 512.264.2740.
